/*
 * Engli writing prompts.
 * Each entry includes a free-writing topic and a model response revealed only
 * after submission. Add another entry here and the writing player and stats
 * catalogue will include it automatically.
 */
const writingsBank = [
  ["Technology & society", "AI in everyday decisions", "Should people allow artificial intelligence to make more everyday decisions for them? Discuss both views and give your opinion.", "Artificial intelligence can save time by comparing information that people would struggle to process alone. However, convenience should not become a reason to surrender responsibility, especially when decisions affect employment, health or personal data. I believe AI should advise rather than decide in these areas. Human judgement may be imperfect, but it can consider context, empathy and values that an automated system cannot fully understand."],
  ["Technology & society", "The value of a digital detox", "Is taking regular breaks from digital devices an effective way to improve modern life?", "Digital breaks can restore attention and make people more aware of their surroundings. They are not a complete solution, since work and relationships increasingly depend on technology, but they can expose unhealthy habits. A sensible approach is to create device-free periods instead of rejecting technology altogether. This preserves its practical benefits while giving people more control over their time."],
  ["Technology & society", "Who should verify online news?", "Should individuals, technology companies or governments take the main responsibility for reducing false information online?", "Individuals should learn to question dramatic claims, but personal responsibility cannot solve a problem created by a global information system. Platforms need transparent standards and governments should protect elections without controlling legitimate debate. The best solution is shared responsibility: companies improve their systems, public institutions teach media literacy and users pause before sharing uncertain material."],
  ["Technology & society", "Smart cities and privacy", "Do the benefits of smart-city technology justify the amount of data collected about citizens?", "Sensors can reduce traffic, improve public services and help cities respond to emergencies. Nevertheless, constant collection of location and behaviour data creates a risk of surveillance without meaningful consent. Smart cities should therefore use the minimum data necessary, publish clear rules and allow independent oversight. Efficiency is valuable, but it should not be purchased at the cost of civic privacy."],
  ["Technology & society", "A shorter digital working week", "Would a shorter working week be more successful if employees were also expected to disconnect from work technology?", "Reducing hours without changing digital expectations would simply compress the same workload into fewer days. A shorter week needs realistic priorities, fewer unnecessary meetings and a clear boundary around messages outside working time. It could improve concentration and wellbeing, but only if organisations measure results rather than rewarding constant availability."],
  ["Technology & society", "Online friendships", "Are friendships formed online as valuable as friendships formed in person?", "Online friendships can offer genuine support, particularly to people who feel isolated in their local communities. They may also be easier to abandon because communication is less connected to shared daily experiences. In my view, value depends on trust and reciprocity rather than location. Digital relationships are real, although they become stronger when people occasionally share experiences beyond a screen."],
  ["Technology & society", "Automation and employment", "Will automation create more opportunities than the jobs it removes?", "Automation will eliminate some repetitive roles while creating demand for technical, creative and interpersonal skills. The transition, however, will not be fair automatically: workers may lose income before training becomes available. Automation can create more opportunities if companies and governments invest in retraining and protect people during change. Without that support, its benefits will be distributed very unevenly."],
  ["Technology & society", "Facial recognition in public", "Should facial-recognition systems be used in public spaces to improve security?", "Facial recognition might help identify suspects quickly, but errors can affect innocent people and the technology can normalise permanent observation. Public use should be limited to serious, clearly defined situations and controlled by courts and independent auditors. General security is not enough to justify a system that changes the relationship between citizens and public space."],
  ["Technology & society", "Algorithms and personal choice", "Do recommendation algorithms broaden people's choices or quietly narrow them?", "Recommendations help users discover music, films and information that match their interests. At the same time, they tend to repeat familiar patterns, making unusual or challenging material less visible. Users should be able to understand and adjust the logic behind recommendations. Algorithms are useful guides, but they should not become invisible editors of personal curiosity."],
  ["Technology & society", "A cashless society", "What are the main advantages and disadvantages of replacing cash with digital payments?", "Digital payments are fast and easier to track, which can reduce some forms of crime and simplify accounting. They also exclude people without reliable internet, bank access or digital confidence, and they create dependence on private systems. A cashless future may be efficient, but it should not arrive before every citizen has a practical alternative."],
  ["Technology & society", "Games as learning tools", "Can video games be an effective part of education?", "Well-designed games can make abstract problems concrete and give learners immediate feedback. Their value depends on the learning objective, since entertainment alone does not guarantee understanding. Schools should use games selectively alongside discussion, reading and practice. In the right context, interactive challenges can motivate students without replacing deeper forms of learning."],
  ["Technology & society", "Phones in classrooms", "Should students be allowed to use smartphones during lessons?", "Smartphones can provide quick access to dictionaries, research and collaborative tools. They can also fragment attention and make it harder for students to participate fully. I favour controlled use: teachers should authorise phones for specific tasks and require them to be put away at other times. The issue is not the device itself, but whether it serves the lesson."],
  ["Technology & society", "Remote collaboration", "What makes collaboration across different time zones successful?", "Remote collaboration works when expectations are explicit. Teams need shared documents, reliable deadlines and a balance between live meetings and written updates so that nobody is disadvantaged by their location. Trust is equally important: managers should assess the quality of work rather than online presence. Good coordination turns distance into flexibility instead of confusion."],
  ["Technology & society", "Influencer marketing", "Does influencer marketing give consumers useful guidance or encourage unnecessary consumption?", "Influencers can explain products in an accessible way and help small businesses reach a wider audience. However, paid recommendations may appear more personal and trustworthy than they really are. Consumers need clear sponsorship labels and enough media literacy to recognise persuasion. Influencer marketing is not inherently harmful, but its intimacy makes honesty especially important."],
  ["Technology & society", "Digital identity", "Should people have greater control over the way their online identity is created and used?", "People should be able to correct inaccurate information and understand who can access their data. Complete control may be impossible because online actions affect other people and public records sometimes serve a legitimate purpose. A fair system would provide transparency, reasonable deletion rights and protection from decisions made by opaque profiles."],
  ["Technology & society", "E-books or paper books", "Are digital books likely to replace printed books completely?", "Digital books are portable, searchable and often cheaper, so they are ideal for travel and quick reference. Printed books remain valuable because they reduce distractions and offer a physical experience many readers remember. The two formats meet different needs. Rather than replacing paper entirely, digital reading will probably expand the range of ways people access books."],
  ["Technology & society", "Open-source software", "Should public institutions prefer open-source software to proprietary alternatives?", "Open-source software can reduce dependence on one supplier and allow experts to inspect how a system works. It still requires maintenance, security reviews and staff with the right skills. Public institutions should choose openly developed tools when they offer reliable long-term value, not simply because they are free. Transparency matters, but quality and responsibility matter too."],
  ["Technology & society", "Translation apps", "Can translation technology replace the need to learn foreign languages?", "Translation apps make travel and basic communication easier, but they often miss tone, cultural reference and implied meaning. Learning a language remains valuable because it changes how people understand other communities and participate in conversation. Technology should support language learning rather than replace it. A tool can translate words without creating the same relationship between speakers."],
  ["Technology & society", "Wearable health data", "Should people share data from wearable devices with health researchers?", "Wearable data could help researchers understand patterns in sleep, movement and illness across large populations. Participants must nevertheless know exactly how their information will be used and how it will be protected. Sharing should be voluntary, anonymised where possible and governed by independent rules. Public benefit cannot justify treating private bodies as unlimited sources of data."],
  ["Technology & society", "Virtual reality", "Will virtual reality improve education and work, or make people more disconnected from real life?", "Virtual reality can place learners inside historical settings or allow teams to practise dangerous tasks safely. Extended use may be tiring and it cannot reproduce every social or physical experience. Its best role is as a focused supplement to real interaction. Virtual environments are powerful when they expand access, not when they encourage people to avoid the world around them."],

  ["Education & learning", "Exams and ability", "Do traditional examinations measure students' abilities accurately?", "Examinations measure performance under pressure and can provide a common standard across schools. They cannot show every important ability, such as collaboration, creativity or gradual improvement. A fair education system should combine exams with projects and coursework. Tests are useful evidence, but they should not become the definition of intelligence."],
  ["Education & learning", "The value of a gap year", "Should students be encouraged to take a gap year before university?", "A gap year can help students gain maturity, work experience and a clearer sense of direction. It may also be inaccessible to those who cannot afford travel or unpaid opportunities. Schools should present it as one possible route and help students plan meaningful activities. Time away from formal education is valuable when it has purpose rather than simply postponing a decision."],
  ["Education & learning", "Homework", "Is regular homework essential for academic progress?", "Homework can reinforce skills and teach students to organise their own time. Excessive or repetitive tasks, however, reduce motivation and widen inequalities when some families can provide more support than others. Schools should set shorter, purposeful assignments and consider students' total workload. Practice matters, but more work is not always better learning."],
  ["Education & learning", "University degrees", "Is a university degree still the best route to a successful career?", "University remains essential for professions that require specialised knowledge and it can develop independence and critical thinking. It is not the only route to a stable career, since apprenticeships and technical training may offer more direct experience. Young people should choose according to their abilities and goals rather than assuming that one qualification guarantees success."],
  ["Education & learning", "Vocational education", "Why should vocational education receive the same respect as academic education?", "Vocational courses develop practical expertise that economies depend on, from healthcare to engineering and construction. They can also provide a faster route into employment without being intellectually simple. Treating them as second-rate discourages capable students and creates skills shortages. Education should be valued for the opportunities it creates, not for how theoretical it sounds."],
  ["Education & learning", "Lifelong learning", "Should employers be responsible for helping workers continue learning throughout their careers?", "Workers benefit from training because industries change faster than many traditional qualifications. Employers also benefit from retaining experienced staff instead of replacing them. Individuals still need to take responsibility for their development, but companies should provide time and access rather than expecting learning to happen after work. Lifelong learning is a shared investment."],
  ["Education & learning", "Language immersion", "Is living abroad the most effective way to learn a language?", "Living abroad creates constant opportunities to hear natural language and use it for real purposes. It is not automatically effective, since some learners remain inside an international social circle. Progress depends on deliberate interaction, feedback and patience. Immersion is powerful, but a motivated learner can also build meaningful exposure without moving countries."],
  ["Education & learning", "Group projects", "Do group projects prepare students better for adult life than individual assignments?", "Group projects teach negotiation, delegation and responsibility for a shared result. They can be frustrating when effort is uneven or assessment ignores individual contributions. Teachers should give groups clear roles and include individual reflection. Collaboration is essential in adult life, but students need guidance to learn it rather than simply being placed in a group."],
  ["Education & learning", "School uniforms", "Should schools require students to wear uniforms?", "Uniforms can reduce visible economic differences and make school identity clearer. They may also limit self-expression and create unnecessary costs when families must buy specialised clothing. A sensible policy would focus on practical, affordable standards rather than strict appearance rules. Respect and belonging are not created by identical clothes alone."],
  ["Education & learning", "Online classes", "Can online classes provide the same quality of education as face-to-face classes?", "Online classes offer flexibility and can connect learners with teachers who live far away. They make participation harder for students with poor internet, limited space or a need for direct support. Quality depends on design: interactive lessons, accessible materials and regular feedback are essential. Online education is a valuable option, but not a universal replacement."],
  ["Education & learning", "Assessing creativity", "How should schools assess creativity without discouraging it?", "Creativity should not be reduced to producing an unusual answer on demand. Teachers can assess the process: how students explore alternatives, explain choices and respond to feedback. Clear criteria can provide fairness while leaving room for different outcomes. The aim is to reward thoughtful risk-taking rather than a single fashionable style."],
  ["Education & learning", "School start times", "Should secondary schools start later in the morning?", "Later starts could improve concentration because teenagers often struggle with very early schedules. Changing timetables may affect parents, transport and after-school activities, so it requires wider planning. Evidence about sleep should nevertheless be taken seriously. A school day should support learning rather than treat tiredness as a sign of discipline."],
  ["Education & learning", "Reading for pleasure", "Why should schools protect time for reading that is not assessed?", "Reading for pleasure develops vocabulary and empathy without making every page feel like a test. Students also learn to choose, persist and form personal interpretations. Assessment has a place, but constant measurement can weaken curiosity. Protecting voluntary reading is an investment in the independent thinking education hopes to create."],
  ["Education & learning", "Teacher authority", "Should teachers focus more on authority or on building friendly relationships with students?", "Students need clear boundaries before learning can be fair and safe. Yet authority based only on fear discourages questions and hides mistakes. Effective teachers combine consistent expectations with respect and approachability. A friendly relationship is not a loss of authority; it can make authority more legitimate."],
  ["Education & learning", "Studying abroad", "What are the main benefits of studying abroad?", "Studying abroad exposes students to different academic approaches and everyday customs. It also requires them to solve ordinary problems independently, which can build confidence. The experience may be expensive and emotionally demanding, so support matters. When accessible, it develops not only knowledge but also the ability to interpret the world from more than one perspective."],
  ["Education & learning", "AI tutors", "Should students use AI tutors as part of their studies?", "AI tutors can explain a difficult point repeatedly and adapt practice to a student's pace. They may also provide confident but inaccurate answers, and excessive use can replace productive struggle. Students should use them as a source of questions and feedback while checking important information with teachers and reliable texts. Technology should extend teaching, not remove human guidance."],
  ["Education & learning", "School meals", "Should schools provide free meals to all students?", "Free school meals can improve concentration and reduce the stigma attached to financial hardship. Universal provision costs more than targeted support, but it avoids complex eligibility tests and benefits families facing temporary difficulty. Meals should be nutritious and culturally respectful. Education is unlikely to be equal when some students are trying to learn while hungry."],
  ["Education & learning", "Adult education", "Why is adult education important in a changing economy?", "Adult education allows people to update skills, change direction and remain involved in civic life. It is particularly important when technology changes jobs faster than school systems can respond. Courses need flexible schedules and affordable fees because adults often have caring and financial responsibilities. Learning should be available across a lifetime, not end at graduation."],
  ["Education & learning", "Class size", "Does reducing class size always improve education?", "Smaller classes can give teachers more time to notice individual needs and provide feedback. The benefit is limited if teaching methods and resources remain weak. Reducing class size should therefore be part of a wider investment in teacher training and materials. Numbers matter, but the quality of attention matters more."],
  ["Education & learning", "Funding priorities", "Should education funding focus first on technology or on teachers?", "Digital equipment can widen access to information, but it cannot replace explanation, encouragement and professional judgement. Funding should first ensure that teachers are well trained and supported, then use technology where it solves a real problem. A modern classroom is not defined by the number of screens, but by the quality of learning they enable."],

  ["Work & the future", "The four-day week", "Should companies move to a four-day working week without reducing salaries?", "A shorter week could improve energy and concentration if organisations remove unnecessary work rather than compress it. Some sectors cannot close for an extra day, although shifts can distribute time differently. The policy should be tested by industry and measured by service quality. Its success depends less on the calendar than on whether productivity is designed intelligently."],
  ["Work & the future", "Changing career", "Is changing career in mid-life a realistic goal?", "A mid-life career change can renew motivation and use skills that have been overlooked. It also carries financial and emotional risks, especially for people with dependants. Preparation, transferable skills and gradual experimentation make the transition more realistic. Age should not decide a person's future, but enthusiasm alone is not a substitute for planning."],
  ["Work & the future", "Work experience", "Should every young person complete work experience before finishing education?", "Work experience can reveal how organisations operate and help students connect theory with practical decisions. It may reproduce inequality if only wealthy students can accept unpaid placements. Schools and employers should offer paid, supervised opportunities with clear learning goals. Experience is valuable when it is educational rather than simply cheap labour."],
  ["Work & the future", "Office presence", "Does working in an office produce better teamwork than working remotely?", "Physical presence makes spontaneous conversation and informal learning easier. Remote work can produce focused collaboration when tools and expectations are clear, and it may include people who cannot relocate. Teams should choose the setting according to the work being done. Mandatory presence is not the same as effective teamwork."],
  ["Work & the future", "Leadership", "What qualities are most important in a good leader?", "A good leader sets a clear direction but remains willing to revise it when evidence changes. Communication, fairness and the ability to listen create trust more reliably than charisma. Leaders must also accept responsibility when decisions fail. Authority is strongest when people understand both the purpose and the limits of power."],
  ["Work & the future", "The gig economy", "Does the gig economy offer freedom or insecurity?", "Short-term work offers flexibility for people who need to choose their hours or combine several activities. It can also transfer business risk to workers who lack paid leave, predictable income and bargaining power. The gig economy should preserve flexibility while guaranteeing basic protections. Freedom is meaningful only when refusing a bad job does not threaten survival."],
  ["Work & the future", "Unpaid internships", "Should unpaid internships be banned?", "Unpaid internships can provide useful experience, but they exclude people who cannot afford to work without income. They also allow organisations to describe ordinary productive work as training. Genuine learning placements should be short, supervised and paid whenever the intern creates value. Opportunity should not depend on family support."],
  ["Work & the future", "Salary transparency", "Would salary transparency make workplaces fairer?", "Publishing salary ranges can expose unjustified differences and give employees better information when negotiating. It may also create tension if roles are difficult to compare or performance is rewarded differently. Transparent criteria are as important as transparent numbers. Openness can improve trust when organisations explain how pay decisions are made."],
  ["Work & the future", "Work-life boundaries", "Who should be responsible for protecting work-life boundaries?", "Individuals can turn off notifications and plan their time, but they cannot create a healthy boundary if managers expect constant replies. Employers should define reasonable contact hours and model them from the top. Workers still need to communicate their limits. Boundaries succeed when personal habits and organisational culture support each other."],
  ["Work & the future", "A job for life", "Is the idea of a job for life still desirable?", "A long career with one organisation can provide security, deep expertise and strong relationships. It may also reduce adaptability if people remain in roles that no longer suit them. Modern workers need both stability and the chance to grow. The best goal is not one employer forever, but a career that remains meaningful and sustainable."],
  ["Work & the future", "Meetings", "Should companies reduce the number of meetings they hold?", "Many meetings exist because decisions and information are not organised clearly. Reducing them can protect concentration, but some discussion requires real-time exchange and shared responsibility. Companies should give every meeting a purpose, invite only necessary participants and record decisions. A short meeting can be useful; a meeting without an outcome is expensive."],
  ["Work & the future", "Professional networking", "Is professional networking more important than technical ability?", "Relationships can help people discover opportunities and understand an industry, but networking cannot compensate for poor work indefinitely. Technical ability creates value while communication allows others to recognise it. Successful careers require both. Networking should be understood as building genuine professional relationships, not collecting contacts for immediate advantage."],
  ["Work & the future", "Coworking spaces", "Do coworking spaces improve productivity for people who work independently?", "Coworking spaces can provide structure, social contact and equipment for people who would otherwise work alone. Noise, cost and constant interaction may reduce concentration for some users. Their value depends on offering both communal and quiet areas. A workplace should support the rhythm of the task rather than impose one style of working."],
  ["Work & the future", "Training for automation", "Should companies pay for workers to retrain when automation changes their roles?", "Companies benefit from automation and should share responsibility for the transition it creates. Retraining cannot guarantee that every worker will remain in the same job, but it can provide a fairer route to new roles. Governments and education providers also have a part to play. Technological progress should include people, not simply replace them."],
  ["Work & the future", "Productivity tracking", "Is monitoring employee productivity an acceptable use of workplace technology?", "Tracking can identify workload problems and help managers plan resources. Detailed surveillance may reduce trust and encourage workers to optimise visible activity rather than meaningful results. Organisations should collect limited data for a clear purpose and discuss it openly. Performance is too complex to be represented by keystrokes or online status alone."],
  ["Work & the future", "Parental leave", "Should parental leave be divided equally between parents?", "Equal leave can support children while reducing the assumption that caring is mainly a mother's responsibility. Families differ, so flexibility is necessary, particularly when health or income is involved. Employers should offer a generous minimum to both parents and avoid penalising those who use it. Shared care benefits families and gradually changes workplace expectations."],
  ["Work & the future", "Promotion criteria", "What should matter most when deciding who deserves a promotion?", "Promotions should reflect sustained performance, judgement and the ability to support others, not only individual visibility. Clear criteria reduce the influence of personal preference and informal networks. Ambition is valuable, but a higher position also requires responsibility. The best candidate is the person prepared to improve the organisation, not merely their title."],
  ["Work & the future", "Job interviews", "Do job interviews predict future performance accurately?", "Interviews reveal how candidates communicate and respond to questions, but they favour people who are comfortable with unfamiliar performance situations. Practical tasks and structured scoring can provide stronger evidence. Interviews should remain part of recruitment, yet employers should not confuse confidence with competence. A fair process measures relevant ability in more than one way."],
  ["Work & the future", "Volunteering and careers", "Can volunteering be as valuable as paid work for career development?", "Volunteering can develop responsibility, teamwork and knowledge of communities that paid roles may not provide. It should not be used to excuse employers from paying workers, especially when the work is essential. As a learning experience, volunteering is valuable when expectations and limits are clear. Its purpose should be contribution as well as personal development."],
  ["Work & the future", "Retirement age", "Should people be encouraged to work beyond the traditional retirement age?", "Longer lives may allow people to continue contributing and sharing expertise. However, not everyone has the same health, job conditions or financial need, so a single expectation would be unfair. Flexible retirement can combine part-time work with rest and caring. Later work should be an option, not a moral duty."],

  ["Environment & cities", "Public transport", "How can cities persuade more people to use public transport?", "People are more likely to leave cars at home when public transport is reliable, frequent and reasonably priced. Campaigns help, but they cannot compensate for long delays or unsafe stations. Cities should improve the service first, then use parking policy and clear information to make the sustainable choice practical rather than merely virtuous."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Car-free centres", "Should city centres become completely car-free?", "Removing cars can reduce pollution, noise and danger while creating space for walking and local businesses. Some residents and deliveries still need controlled access, so a complete ban may require exceptions. The best schemes combine pedestrian areas with public transport and accessible alternatives. A quieter centre is worthwhile when mobility is planned fairly."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Who should recycle?", "Is recycling mainly the responsibility of consumers or of manufacturers?", "Consumers must sort waste carefully, but they make choices within a system designed by producers. Manufacturers should reduce unnecessary packaging and make materials easier to reuse. Individuals can support change, yet responsibility is unfair when companies decide what products look like and cities provide inconsistent collection. Recycling needs action at every stage."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Renewable energy", "Should governments prioritise renewable energy even if it increases short-term costs?", "Renewable energy requires investment, but it can reduce pollution and dependence on imported fuel over time. Costs should not be ignored because households with low incomes are affected first by price rises. Governments should combine clean infrastructure with targeted support. Delaying transition may appear cheaper, but it transfers larger costs to the future."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Plastic bans", "Are bans on single-use plastics the most effective way to reduce waste?", "Bans can remove a common source of unnecessary waste and encourage better design. They are less effective when affordable alternatives are unavailable or when policy ignores industrial packaging. A ban should form part of wider measures including reuse, producer responsibility and reliable collection. Strong rules work best when practical options exist."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Urban trees", "Why should cities invest in trees and green spaces?", "Trees cool streets, absorb some pollution and make dense areas more pleasant. Their benefits are uneven if wealthy neighbourhoods receive most of the investment, and planting without long-term care wastes money. Urban greenery should be treated as essential infrastructure and distributed according to need. It improves both environmental resilience and everyday life."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Tourism and nature", "Can tourism protect natural areas as well as damage them?", "Tourism can provide income for conservation and help visitors value landscapes they might otherwise ignore. Large numbers, however, increase waste, water use and pressure on habitats. Protection requires limits, local control and transparent use of visitor fees. Tourism supports nature only when the environment is treated as more than a product."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Local food", "Should people try to buy locally produced food whenever possible?", "Local food can support farmers and reduce some transport emissions, while also strengthening regional economies. It is not always the most sustainable choice because production methods and storage matter more than distance alone. Consumers should value seasonal, well-produced food rather than assuming a local label guarantees a small environmental footprint."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Water use", "Should households pay more for excessive water consumption?", "A higher price for excessive use could discourage waste, especially during droughts. Water is a basic need, so the policy must protect ordinary households and distinguish essential use from luxury consumption. Clear information, efficient infrastructure and fair pricing should work together. Punishing people without fixing leaks would be both ineffective and unjust."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Climate adaptation", "Should cities spend more on adapting to climate change than on reducing emissions?", "Cities must protect residents from heat, floods and storms that are already becoming more severe. Adaptation does not remove the need to reduce emissions, since prevention limits future damage. Budgets should connect both aims: shaded streets and efficient buildings can improve present safety while lowering long-term emissions."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Nuclear energy", "Should nuclear energy remain part of a low-carbon energy strategy?", "Nuclear power can produce large amounts of electricity with low operational emissions and reliable output. Waste, cost and accident risk require serious management, so it cannot be treated as a simple solution. Countries should compare it honestly with renewables and storage. The right mix will depend on safety, geography and long-term planning."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Fast fashion", "Why is fast fashion difficult to make sustainable?", "Fast fashion encourages frequent purchases through low prices and rapidly changing styles. Recycling alone cannot solve the energy, water and labour problems created before clothing is discarded. Consumers can buy less and repair more, but companies must also design durable products and disclose supply chains. Sustainability requires changing the business model, not just the packaging."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Cycling", "What would make cycling a realistic transport choice for more people?", "People cycle more when routes are safe, connected and separated from fast traffic. Bike lanes alone are not enough if they disappear at dangerous junctions or if secure storage is unavailable. Cities should design for ordinary users rather than only experienced cyclists. Reliable infrastructure can make a healthy choice feel normal instead of risky."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Green buildings", "Should new buildings be required to meet strict environmental standards?", "Buildings last for decades, so weak standards create long-term energy costs and emissions. Strict rules may raise construction prices, but incentives and support can prevent the burden falling on low-income buyers. Environmental standards should be ambitious and practical, including insulation, materials and future repair. Building cheaply today can be expensive tomorrow."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Flood defences", "Should communities protect every area from flooding or allow some land to return to nature?", "Protective walls can save homes and infrastructure, but they are expensive and may move water towards neighbouring areas. In some places, restoring wetlands and relocating the most exposed buildings is safer in the long term. Decisions should combine engineering with local knowledge. Protection is not always the same as permanent resistance."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Rural depopulation", "How can governments make rural areas more attractive to young people?", "Rural communities need reliable transport, fast internet, schools and meaningful employment rather than occasional publicity campaigns. Housing and local services matter because young people need a complete life, not only a picturesque setting. Supporting small businesses and remote work can help, but decisions should be shaped by residents rather than imposed from cities."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Noise pollution", "Should noise pollution be treated as seriously as other forms of pollution?", "Persistent noise affects sleep, concentration and mental health, even though it is less visible than smoke or rubbish. Cities should measure it, enforce limits and protect quiet areas. Residents also need realistic transport and nightlife policies rather than blanket bans. A healthy environment includes the soundscape in which people live."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Community gardens", "Do community gardens offer a meaningful response to urban environmental problems?", "Community gardens cannot feed an entire city, but they create habitat, teach practical skills and strengthen relationships between neighbours. Their impact is social as well as environmental. Cities should provide secure land and water while allowing residents to shape the projects. Small spaces matter when they encourage wider responsibility for shared places."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Environmental education", "Should environmental education be a compulsory part of the school curriculum?", "All students need to understand how daily choices connect to wider ecological systems. Education should avoid creating guilt without offering practical action, and it should include science, economics and civic decision-making. A compulsory foundation is justified because environmental problems affect everyone. Learning should lead to informed participation rather than fear."],
  ["Environment & cities", "Climate migration", "How should cities prepare for people displaced by climate change?", "Cities should plan housing, schools and healthcare before emergency arrivals place pressure on existing services. Newcomers need more than shelter: they need a route into work and community life. Planning must include current residents so that solidarity does not become competition for scarce resources. A safe arrival is both a practical and social process."],

  ["Health & lifestyle", "The importance of sleep", "Should employers and schools do more to protect people's sleep?", "Sleep is often described as a personal habit, but schedules and long commutes can make healthy routines difficult. Schools and employers should consider the effects of early starts and unpredictable hours. Individuals still control many choices, yet public policy can create better conditions. Rest is not laziness; it is part of mental and physical performance."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Mental health at work", "What should workplaces do to support employees' mental health?", "Workplaces should reduce unnecessary pressure, train managers to notice distress and offer confidential support. A wellbeing app cannot compensate for impossible workloads or a culture that rewards silence. Employees also need to communicate their limits, but responsibility must be shared. Mental health improves when support is built into ordinary management rather than offered only in crisis."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Exercise and motivation", "Why do many people find it difficult to maintain regular exercise?", "People often begin with unrealistic goals and then interpret a missed session as failure. Exercise becomes more sustainable when it is convenient, enjoyable and connected to a routine. Public spaces and flexible work can help, but motivation should not be the only strategy. Small, repeatable actions are more effective than occasional bursts of ambition."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Processed food", "Should governments regulate the sale of highly processed food?", "Highly processed food is convenient and affordable, so regulation must not punish families with limited time or income. Clear labels, restrictions on marketing to children and healthier public meals can influence choices without banning everything. Individuals matter, but companies design the food environment. Good policy makes the healthier option easier to recognise and afford."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Public health campaigns", "Are public health campaigns more effective when they use fear or positive messages?", "Fear can make a risk memorable, but excessive alarm may cause people to disengage or distrust authorities. Positive messages show practical steps and give people a sense of control. Campaigns should be honest about risk while explaining what action helps. Respectful communication is more likely to build long-term trust than shock alone."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Technology in healthcare", "Will healthcare technology improve access to treatment?", "Telemedicine and digital records can reduce travel and help specialists share information. They may exclude people without devices or make complex care feel impersonal. Technology should expand access while preserving face-to-face options and strong data protection. Innovation is valuable when it supports relationships rather than treating patients as technical problems."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Screen time", "Should parents impose strict limits on children's screen time?", "Children need boundaries because screens can displace sleep, movement and conversation. A simple number of minutes cannot reflect whether the content is educational, social or passive. Parents should set predictable limits and model balanced use themselves. The aim is to develop judgement, not make technology seem forbidden."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Vaccination", "Should vaccination be compulsory for participation in certain public services?", "Vaccination protects individuals and reduces risks for people who cannot be vaccinated. Compulsion is a serious limit on personal choice and should be used only when evidence shows a clear public danger. Policies need exemptions, accessible services and transparent information. Public trust is strengthened when rules are proportionate and explained honestly."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Mindfulness", "Can mindfulness make a significant difference to modern stress levels?", "Mindfulness can help people notice thoughts and react less automatically to pressure. It is not a cure for poverty, unsafe work or serious illness, so presenting it as a universal solution is unfair. Used alongside practical changes and professional care, it can be a useful skill. Calm attention is valuable, but context still matters."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Sport at school", "Should schools give more time to physical education?", "Physical education supports health, confidence and cooperation, and it can improve concentration in other lessons. It should not be reduced to competitive sport because students have different abilities. More time would be worthwhile if activities were inclusive and varied. Education develops the whole person, not only academic performance."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Medical self-diagnosis", "Does online health information help people take control or encourage dangerous self-diagnosis?", "Reliable information can help patients prepare questions and recognise when professional advice is needed. Search results also present rare conditions dramatically and cannot examine an individual. People should use online sources as a starting point and check important concerns with qualified professionals. Empowerment requires understanding the limits of information."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Breaks at work", "Should employers require regular breaks during the working day?", "Regular breaks protect concentration and can reduce physical strain, especially in sedentary or repetitive jobs. Employees may avoid them if the workplace rewards visible busyness, so managers must make breaks legitimate. A break is not wasted time when it prevents mistakes and exhaustion. Sustainable performance depends on recovery as well as effort."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "A tax on sugar", "Would a tax on sugary drinks improve public health?", "A sugar tax can encourage reformulation and make consumers notice the cost of unhealthy products. It may affect low-income households more heavily, so revenue should support affordable healthy food and health services. Tax is one tool, not a complete answer. Education and product design must accompany it."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Social connection", "Why is social connection important for physical health?", "Relationships provide emotional support and can encourage people to seek help, move more and maintain routines. Social contact is not equally accessible, so telling isolated people simply to socialise is inadequate. Communities can create welcoming activities and public spaces. Health is partly personal, but belonging is also shaped by society."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Healthy ageing", "What can societies do to help people age healthily?", "Healthy ageing depends on accessible healthcare, safe housing, social contact and opportunities to remain active. It should not be framed only as an individual's responsibility because income and neighbourhoods influence choices. Older people also need a voice in policy. Ageing well means preserving independence and participation, not chasing youth."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Health insurance", "Should healthcare be treated as a public service rather than a consumer product?", "Healthcare involves choices that people cannot always postpone or compare like ordinary purchases. Public systems can protect citizens from financial ruin, although they require taxation and careful management. Private options may exist, but basic treatment should depend on need rather than wealth. A healthy society benefits when nobody fears seeking care."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Outdoor life", "Do people need regular contact with nature to stay healthy?", "Time outdoors can reduce stress, encourage movement and provide a break from artificial environments. Access is unequal in dense or polluted areas, so individual advice is not enough. Cities should protect parks and create safe routes to them. Nature is not a luxury if it supports ordinary physical and mental health."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Pets and wellbeing", "Can keeping a pet improve a person's wellbeing?", "Pets can provide routine, companionship and a reason to move outside. They also require time, money and stable housing, so they are not suitable for everyone. The benefits are real when ownership is responsible. People should choose a pet according to their capacity to care, not only their desire for company."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Alcohol policy", "Should governments do more to reduce harmful alcohol consumption?", "Governments can regulate advertising, improve treatment and make risk information clearer. Excessive restriction may encourage people to ignore sensible advice, while the social costs of addiction are too serious to leave entirely to personal choice. Effective policy combines prevention with compassionate support. The aim is healthier behaviour, not moral judgement."],
  ["Health & lifestyle", "Healthy routines", "Is consistency more important than intensity when developing healthy habits?", "Consistent routines make behaviour less dependent on temporary motivation. Intense effort can be useful for particular goals, but it often becomes unsustainable when daily life changes. A moderate habit repeated over time usually creates a stronger foundation. Health is built through ordinary decisions that can survive busy weeks."],

  ["Culture & media", "Free museums", "Should museums offer free entry to everyone?", "Free entry removes a financial barrier and encourages people to see museums as public spaces rather than occasional luxuries. Museums still need funding for staff, conservation and exhibitions, so governments must replace lost ticket income. A mixed model with free permanent collections and paid special events could widen access without weakening institutions."],
  ["Culture & media", "Streaming films", "Has streaming improved the way people discover films?", "Streaming gives viewers access to films from different countries and periods without travelling to a specialist cinema. Recommendation systems can nevertheless make popular content more visible and reduce shared cultural experiences. Viewers benefit when platforms invest in discovery tools and preserve diverse catalogues. Convenience should broaden choice, not quietly narrow it."],
  ["Culture & media", "Local journalism", "Why is local journalism important in a digital age?", "Local journalists investigate decisions that national media may overlook, such as planning, schools and public spending. Their work is difficult to fund because online advertising rewards scale rather than community value. Supporting local reporting strengthens accountability and belonging. A democracy needs information about the places where people actually live."],
  ["Culture & media", "Preserving dialects", "Should schools help preserve local dialects and minority languages?", "Dialects carry history, identity and ways of expressing relationships that standard language may not capture. Schools should teach students to value linguistic variety while also providing the standard forms needed for wider communication. Preservation is not a rejection of change. It is a way of ensuring that progress does not erase voices."],
  ["Culture & media", "Funding the arts", "Should public money be used to fund the arts?", "The arts create shared experiences, support employment and allow societies to question themselves. Funding decisions must be transparent because public money is limited and not every project can be supported. Commercial popularity should not be the only measure of value. Public investment can protect ambitious work that markets alone would not sustain."],
  ["Culture & media", "Celebrity culture", "Does celebrity culture influence young people too strongly?", "Celebrities can use their visibility to support useful causes and inspire creative ambition. Constant exposure also turns private life into entertainment and can confuse popularity with achievement. Young people need media literacy rather than blanket restrictions. Admiration is harmless when audiences understand that public images are carefully constructed."],
  ["Culture & media", "How to read news", "Should people read news from several sources rather than rely on one?", "Several sources reveal different priorities and make it easier to notice missing context. Reading too much can create confusion when outlets repeat rumours or use different standards. Readers should compare reliable sources and slow down when a claim is emotionally powerful. Media diversity is useful only when combined with critical attention."],
  ["Culture & media", "Public libraries", "What role should public libraries play today?", "Libraries provide books, internet access, quiet space and assistance with information. Their importance has increased because abundance makes reliable selection harder, not because digital tools have made them obsolete. Libraries should adapt without abandoning their core mission: giving people fair, deliberate access to knowledge."],
  ["Culture & media", "Subtitles", "Do subtitles help people understand other cultures or encourage poor language learning habits?", "Subtitles make international films accessible and expose viewers to natural rhythm and expression. If learners always read translations, they may avoid developing listening skills. The solution is to use subtitles strategically, moving between languages as confidence improves. Access and active learning can support each other."],
  ["Culture & media", "Cultural festivals", "Can cultural festivals strengthen communities without reducing cultures to stereotypes?", "Festivals create opportunities for people to share food, music and history with neighbours. They become superficial when cultures are presented as fixed performances rather than living communities. Organisers should involve local people and include difficult as well as celebratory stories. Celebration is strongest when it allows complexity."],
  ["Culture & media", "Book adaptations", "Are film adaptations of books valuable even when they change the original story?", "A film cannot reproduce every inner thought or detail from a novel, so change is inevitable. A good adaptation captures the central tension while using the strengths of cinema rather than copying scenes mechanically. Readers should treat the two works as related interpretations. Fidelity is less important than whether the adaptation has artistic integrity."],
  ["Culture & media", "Advertising", "Should advertising aimed at children be more strictly controlled?", "Children have less experience of persuasion and may not understand why an advert is designed to influence them. Limits on unhealthy products and manipulative techniques are justified, although families and schools also teach critical thinking. Advertising can inform, but children deserve extra protection because their judgement is still developing."],
  ["Culture & media", "Podcasts", "Why have podcasts become an important form of communication?", "Podcasts allow people to explore a subject in depth and hear voices that traditional broadcasting may ignore. Their informal style can create trust, but it can also make unsupported opinions sound authoritative. Listeners should value curiosity while checking important claims. Podcasts are powerful because they combine intimacy with accessible production."],
  ["Culture & media", "Historical monuments", "Should controversial historical monuments be removed or reinterpreted?", "Removing a monument can acknowledge that a public space no longer accepts the values it represents. Leaving it in place with clear context can also teach people how history has been contested. The right response depends on the object and its setting. What matters is that public memory is not allowed to appear neutral."],
  ["Culture & media", "Media bias", "Is completely objective journalism possible?", "Journalists choose which events to cover, which voices to quote and which context to include, so complete neutrality may be impossible. Professional standards can still reduce bias through evidence, corrections and transparent methods. Readers should expect fairness rather than pretend that every report comes from nowhere."],
  ["Culture & media", "Traditional crafts", "Why should traditional crafts be preserved?", "Traditional crafts contain practical knowledge about materials, place and community history. Preservation should not freeze them in the past; crafts survive when people can adapt them and earn a fair income. Teaching these skills connects generations and offers an alternative to disposable production. Living traditions need use, not only display."],
  ["Culture & media", "Music education", "Should music education be compulsory in schools?", "Music develops listening, memory and cooperation, and it gives students a form of expression that academic subjects may not provide. Compulsory lessons should include varied traditions rather than reward only expensive classical training. Every student should experience music, even if not everyone wants to perform publicly."],
  ["Culture & media", "Public art", "Does public art improve the quality of urban life?", "Public art can make ordinary spaces memorable and invite people to discuss their surroundings. It can also consume funds or feel imposed when residents have no voice. Projects should be accessible, well maintained and connected to local stories. Art belongs in public life when it creates dialogue rather than simply decorating property."],
  ["Culture & media", "Comedy and limits", "Should comedians be free to joke about every subject?", "Comedy often challenges power by making uncomfortable subjects discussable. Freedom does not remove the consequences of language, particularly when jokes target people with less power rather than institutions. Audiences should be able to criticise harmful material without demanding that all comedy be safe. The strongest comedy knows the difference between risk and cruelty."],
  ["Culture & media", "Cultural borrowing", "When does cultural borrowing become cultural appropriation?", "Cultures have always influenced one another, and creative exchange can produce valuable new forms. Borrowing becomes exploitative when a powerful group profits from symbols while ignoring or stereotyping the people who created them. Credit, context and participation matter. Respectful exchange is possible when influence is not separated from responsibility."],

  ["Science & ethics", "Gene editing", "Should gene editing be used to prevent serious inherited diseases?", "Gene editing could reduce suffering for families facing severe inherited conditions. It also raises safety and equality concerns, particularly if treatments become available only to wealthy patients or extend from therapy to enhancement. Strict oversight and public debate are essential. Preventing disease is a stronger justification than designing preferred characteristics."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Animal research", "Can animal research be ethically justified?", "Animal research has contributed to important medical knowledge, but the suffering involved cannot be ignored. Researchers should use alternatives whenever possible, reduce the number of animals and apply strict welfare standards. The ethical question is not simply whether a benefit exists, but whether the method is necessary and proportionate."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Space exploration", "Should governments spend money on space exploration when problems on Earth remain unsolved?", "Space exploration produces knowledge and technologies that can benefit life on Earth. Its budgets should nevertheless be compared honestly with urgent needs such as healthcare and climate adaptation. Exploration is defensible when investment is proportionate and international, rather than a symbol of prestige that ignores present suffering."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Climate engineering", "Should scientists investigate technologies that could deliberately cool the planet?", "Research could help governments understand emergency options if climate damage becomes extreme. Deploying such technology might create unknown ecological effects and reduce pressure to cut emissions. Investigation should be transparent and international, while emissions reduction remains the main strategy. Studying a risky option is not the same as treating it as a solution."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Scientific funding", "Should research funding favour projects with immediate practical benefits?", "Applied research can address urgent problems and show taxpayers visible value. Basic research often creates discoveries that could not have been predicted, so a system focused only on quick results would weaken future knowledge. Funding should balance public needs with curiosity-driven work. Science advances when usefulness and uncertainty coexist."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Research data privacy", "How should researchers balance open data with participants' privacy?", "Open data allows other researchers to check results and discover new patterns. Personal information may nevertheless be impossible to anonymise completely, especially when datasets are combined. Researchers should minimise collection, obtain meaningful consent and share only what is necessary. Scientific openness must not turn participants into permanent public records."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Laboratory animals", "Should laboratories be required to publish how many animals are used in research?", "Publishing numbers and welfare outcomes would make institutions more accountable and help the public judge necessity. Data should be accompanied by context because a number alone cannot show the complexity of a study. Transparency may be uncomfortable, but secrecy makes ethical improvement harder."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Scientific misinformation", "Why does scientific misinformation spread so easily?", "Scientific claims are often complex, while misinformation offers simple explanations and emotional certainty. Social platforms reward speed and conflict, and people may distrust experts whose conclusions change with evidence. Better communication requires plain language, visible uncertainty and trusted local voices. Correcting misinformation is not only a matter of providing more facts."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Genetic testing", "Should people be able to access genetic tests without medical advice?", "Direct access can help people ask informed questions and discover risks they might otherwise ignore. Results may be uncertain, misunderstood or emotionally damaging, and they can affect relatives who did not consent. Testing should be available with clear counselling and protection against discrimination. Information is useful only when people can interpret it responsibly."],
  ["Science & ethics", "AI diagnosis", "Can artificial intelligence improve medical diagnosis without weakening the doctor-patient relationship?", "AI can detect patterns in scans and records that a tired human might miss. Doctors still need to explain uncertainty, understand personal context and take responsibility for decisions. The best model treats AI as a second opinion rather than an invisible authority. Trust depends on keeping human judgement visible."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Archaeology and ownership", "Who should own objects discovered by archaeologists?", "Objects found in the ground may have deep meaning for local communities and national history, even when museums elsewhere can preserve them well. Ownership should involve legal rights, local consultation and shared access. Archaeology should not repeat the extraction that shaped colonial collections. Preservation is not a justification for ignoring origin."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Deep-sea mining", "Should deep-sea mining be allowed if it provides minerals for clean technology?", "Minerals are needed for batteries and renewable infrastructure, but deep-sea ecosystems are poorly understood and may recover extremely slowly. A temporary supply problem does not justify irreversible damage without strong evidence of safety. Recycling and alternative materials should be developed before mining begins. Clean technology must not hide a new environmental cost."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Scientific uncertainty", "How should scientists communicate uncertainty to the public?", "Uncertainty is part of honest science, not evidence that researchers know nothing. Scientists should explain what is established, what is likely and what remains unknown in language people can understand. False certainty damages trust when predictions change. Clear uncertainty helps citizens make decisions without pretending that risk can be eliminated."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Access to research", "Should publicly funded research be freely available to everyone?", "People who fund research through taxes should be able to read its results, and open access can accelerate further discoveries. Publishing still costs money, so funding models must not shift the burden onto researchers or less wealthy institutions. Public availability should be the default, accompanied by accessible summaries rather than paywalls alone."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Drones", "Should the use of drones be more strictly regulated?", "Drones can support emergency services, conservation and efficient delivery. They can also disturb privacy and create safety risks in crowded areas. Regulation should distinguish responsible uses from intrusive ones, require visible identification and punish misuse. New technology needs clear boundaries before public trust is lost."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Food labelling", "Should food labels include more scientific information about environmental impact?", "Environmental labels could help consumers compare the hidden effects of different products. Measurements are complex and can create false precision if methods are not transparent. Labels should use understandable categories and be combined with regulation of producers. Information helps, but responsibility cannot be transferred entirely to shoppers."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Autonomous vehicles", "Are autonomous vehicles safer than human-driven vehicles likely to become?", "Machines do not become tired or distracted, so they could reduce many common accidents. Rare situations and decisions about risk remain difficult, especially when systems fail in unfamiliar conditions. Trials should be gradual and data should be shared publicly. Safety claims must be based on real performance rather than technological optimism."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Human enhancement", "Should society distinguish between medical treatment and human enhancement?", "Treating illness aims to restore opportunities that disease removes, while enhancement may create competitive advantages. The boundary is not always clear, but access and social pressure make the distinction important. Regulation should focus on safety, fairness and consent rather than assuming every improvement is automatically desirable."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Citizen science", "Can ordinary citizens make a valuable contribution to scientific research?", "Citizen scientists can collect observations across large areas and help communities understand local change. Their data needs training, clear methods and expert review because enthusiasm does not remove error. Participation is most valuable when contributors receive feedback and recognition. Science becomes stronger when people can both produce and understand evidence."],
  ["Science & ethics", "Explaining science", "Why should scientists learn to communicate beyond academic journals?", "Public decisions about health, technology and the environment depend on scientific knowledge. If experts communicate only with specialists, other voices may fill the gap with confident misinformation. Communication should not simplify evidence into slogans, but it should explain methods, limits and consequences. Public understanding is part of scientific responsibility."],

  ["Travel & community", "Tourism and housing", "Should popular tourist destinations limit the number of visitors they receive?", "Visitor limits can protect historic sites, local housing and fragile ecosystems from being overwhelmed. Tourism provides jobs, so restrictions must be designed with residents and businesses rather than imposed suddenly. Sustainable destinations value quality and local benefit over endless growth. A place should remain liveable for the people who call it home."],
  ["Travel & community", "Solo travel", "What can people learn from travelling alone?", "Solo travel requires people to make decisions, manage uncertainty and communicate with strangers. It can also be lonely or unsafe, particularly without preparation. Travelling alone is valuable when it is approached with humility rather than as a performance of independence. The experience teaches self-reliance while revealing the importance of community."],
  ["Travel & community", "Public parks", "Why are public parks important in growing cities?", "Parks provide space for exercise, rest and contact between people from different backgrounds. They also reduce heat and support urban wildlife. Investment should be distributed fairly because a park is not truly public if some neighbourhoods lack safe access. Green space is part of social infrastructure, not an optional decoration."],
  ["Travel & community", "Migration and identity", "Does migration weaken national identity or make it more diverse?", "Migration can change familiar customs and create genuine tensions about belonging. It also brings languages, skills and relationships that enrich public life. National identity has never been completely fixed, so adaptation is unavoidable. A confident society can preserve valued traditions while allowing new citizens to participate in defining the future."],
  ["Travel & community", "Volunteering abroad", "Is volunteering abroad always a positive experience for local communities?", "International volunteers may bring useful skills and resources, but short visits can also displace local workers or turn hardship into a tourist experience. Projects should be designed by local organisations and measured by long-term benefit. Good intentions are not enough. Responsible volunteering begins with listening and accepts that outsiders are not always needed."],
  ["Travel & community", "Urban tourism", "How can cities benefit from tourism without losing their character?", "Cities can direct visitors towards less crowded areas, support local businesses and limit activities that damage housing or public space. Residents should have a voice in tourism planning because they experience its costs every day. A city keeps its character when visitors participate respectfully rather than consume a staged version of local life."],
  ["Travel & community", "Second homes", "Should governments restrict the number of second homes in popular regions?", "Second homes can support construction and tourism, but large numbers reduce the supply of housing for permanent residents and leave neighbourhoods empty for much of the year. Restrictions or taxes may be justified where local people cannot afford to stay. Property rights matter, but communities also need a living population."],
  ["Travel & community", "Intercultural friendships", "What helps friendships between people from different cultures succeed?", "Curiosity and patience allow people to ask about differences without treating one person as a representative of an entire culture. Misunderstandings are inevitable, so trust grows when friends can discuss them openly. Shared activities create a practical basis for connection. Intercultural friendship is built through ordinary reliability, not perfect knowledge."],
  ["Travel & community", "Public celebrations", "Should public celebrations reflect every community in a city?", "Shared celebrations can help residents recognise histories and traditions beyond their own. Representation should not become a competition for symbolic space, and events must be accessible rather than merely decorative. A city can create a common identity by making room for several stories. Inclusion works when communities help shape the event."],
  ["Travel & community", "Small towns", "Can small towns offer a better quality of life than large cities?", "Small towns may provide quieter surroundings, lower pressure and stronger informal relationships. They can lack specialist services, public transport and varied employment, especially for young adults. Quality of life depends on priorities and access. A town is attractive when it combines community with the services people need to remain independent."],
  ["Travel & community", "Language barriers", "What should public services do to support people who do not speak the dominant language?", "Translation and interpretation allow residents to access healthcare, education and legal rights while they learn the local language. Services should encourage language learning without using it as a reason to deny urgent help. Clear communication protects everyone. Inclusion is practical infrastructure, not a favour to newcomers."],
  ["Travel & community", "Travel and carbon", "Should people fly less often to reduce environmental damage?", "Air travel connects families and supports economies, but its emissions are difficult to justify when journeys are purely optional and alternatives exist. Individuals can choose trains or combine trips, while governments and airlines must improve technology and pricing. Responsible travel is not about never moving, but about recognising the real cost of convenience."],
  ["Travel & community", "Local traditions", "How can communities preserve local traditions while remaining open to change?", "Traditions survive when people practise and reinterpret them, not when they are treated as museum objects. Younger residents should have permission to change forms while keeping the values that matter. Documentation and teaching can help, but participation is essential. A living tradition welcomes new voices without forgetting its origins."],
  ["Travel & community", "Airports", "Should airports be expanded to support economic growth?", "Airport expansion can create jobs and improve connections, yet it also increases noise, emissions and pressure on nearby communities. Projects should be approved only after comparing alternatives and requiring environmental safeguards. Growth is not automatically beneficial if its costs are local and its profits are distant."],
  ["Travel & community", "Hosting visitors", "What responsibilities do visitors have when staying in someone's home?", "Visitors should respect routines, privacy and the resources of their hosts rather than behave like customers in a hotel. Asking questions and contributing to ordinary tasks show gratitude. Hosts also need to communicate expectations clearly. Hospitality works best as a relationship with mutual consideration, not as a one-sided service."],
  ["Travel & community", "Community events", "Why do community events matter in an increasingly individualistic society?", "Community events create repeated opportunities for neighbours to recognise one another and cooperate outside formal institutions. Their value is not measured only by attendance; a small group can still create trust. Events should be affordable and inclusive so they do not become another form of social exclusion. Belonging grows through shared time."],
  ["Travel & community", "Internet in rural areas", "Should governments guarantee reliable internet access in remote communities?", "Internet access now affects education, healthcare, employment and communication, so remote areas should not be treated as commercially irrelevant. Infrastructure is expensive, but public investment can create opportunities that private markets overlook. Connectivity will not solve every rural problem, yet without it many solutions remain out of reach."],
  ["Travel & community", "Cultural etiquette", "Is it important for travellers to learn local etiquette before visiting a country?", "Basic knowledge of greetings, dress and public behaviour prevents avoidable offence and shows respect. Travellers cannot learn every detail, so they should remain observant and willing to apologise. Etiquette is not a test of cultural perfection. It is a way of recognising that visitors are guests in someone else's social environment."],
  ["Travel & community", "Travel as education", "Is travelling an effective form of education?", "Travel provides direct experience of geography, history and social difference that books cannot fully reproduce. It can also reinforce stereotypes if visitors move through places without listening. Education depends on reflection and interaction, not distance alone. A thoughtful journey changes the questions people ask after they return."],
  ["Travel & community", "Tourism employment", "Does tourism create secure employment for local residents?", "Tourism can generate many jobs quickly, but seasonal work and low wages may leave workers vulnerable. Local training, fair contracts and support for locally owned businesses can keep more value in the community. Tourism employment is beneficial when residents have a voice in the industry and are not dependent on unpredictable visitor numbers."],

  ["Consumer & economy", "Online shopping", "Has online shopping improved consumers' lives overall?", "Online shopping saves time and gives people access to products that local shops may not carry. It can increase packaging, delivery traffic and pressure on small businesses. Consumers benefit when they compare the convenience with its wider cost. Online retail should become more sustainable rather than simply more efficient at selling more."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Local businesses", "Why should people support local businesses even when large chains are cheaper?", "Local businesses keep more money in the community and often provide personal knowledge and flexible service. Large chains can offer lower prices, which matters to households under pressure. The solution is not to romanticise every local shop, but to create fair conditions in which independent businesses can compete. Communities need both affordability and local choice."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Second-hand goods", "Should buying second-hand become the normal choice for more products?", "Second-hand buying reduces waste and allows people to access quality goods at lower prices. It may be inconvenient or impossible for hygiene-sensitive and highly specialised products. Repair, resale and durable design should work together. Choosing used items challenges the idea that responsible consumption always requires buying something new."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Inflation and habits", "How can households adapt to rising prices without reducing their quality of life excessively?", "Households can review subscriptions, plan meals and distinguish essential spending from automatic habits. These choices cannot solve inflation for people already struggling with rent or energy bills. Governments must protect basic living standards while individuals gain control where possible. Financial resilience is partly personal and partly political."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Universal basic income", "Would a universal basic income improve society?", "A universal payment could reduce insecurity and simplify complicated welfare systems. It would be expensive and might be insufficient without strong public services, while some people need targeted support. The idea deserves testing rather than slogans. Income security should give people freedom to care, learn and change work, not replace every social institution."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Financial education", "Should personal finance be compulsory at school?", "Students should understand interest, contracts, taxes and budgeting before making adult decisions. Financial education must be practical and inclusive because families have different resources and experiences. It cannot eliminate poverty, but it can prevent avoidable mistakes and make financial institutions easier to question. Knowing how money works is a form of independence."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Subscription services", "Have subscription services made consumers less aware of how much they spend?", "Small monthly payments feel harmless, but several subscriptions can become a significant fixed cost. Automatic renewal and difficult cancellation make the problem worse. Consumers should review services regularly, while companies should make prices and cancellation simple. Convenience is fair only when people can see and control the commitment."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Ethical consumption", "Is ethical consumption a realistic way to change business behaviour?", "Buying choices can reward responsible companies and signal demand for better products. Consumers have limited information and often cannot afford the most ethical option, so purchasing cannot replace regulation. Ethical consumption is useful when combined with political pressure and producer responsibility. Individuals should act, but they should not carry the entire burden."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Advertising to children", "Should advertising products to children be restricted?", "Children are less able to recognise persuasive intent and may pressure families to buy unnecessary products. Restrictions are especially justified for unhealthy food and gambling-like games. Parents and schools still teach critical thinking, but they cannot compete with constant commercial exposure alone. Protecting children requires limits on the most manipulative practices."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Cashless payments", "What are the risks of a society that relies entirely on cashless payments?", "Digital payments are convenient and can reduce some administrative costs. A technical failure, cyberattack or lack of bank access can suddenly exclude people who depend on the system. Cash and offline alternatives remain important for resilience. Modern finance should be efficient without becoming a single point of failure."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Growth and wellbeing", "Should governments measure success through wellbeing rather than economic growth alone?", "Economic growth can fund services and create opportunities, but it does not show how wealth is distributed or whether people feel secure. Wellbeing measures can reveal health, housing and environmental conditions that GDP misses. Governments should use both sets of indicators. Prosperity is meaningful only when it improves ordinary lives."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Food prices", "Should governments intervene when essential food prices rise sharply?", "Temporary support can protect families during shocks, but permanent price controls may create shortages or discourage production. Governments should combine targeted help with action on supply chains and competition. Food is a basic need, so leaving vulnerable households completely exposed is unacceptable. Intervention should be focused and transparent."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Repair over replacement", "Should manufacturers be required to make products easier to repair?", "Repairable products reduce waste and give consumers more control over the cost of ownership. Manufacturers may argue that strict rules increase prices, but disposable design also hides environmental and financial costs. Repair information, spare parts and reasonable warranties should be standard. A product should not become useless because one small component fails."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Fair trade", "Can fair-trade labels guarantee that workers receive fair treatment?", "Fair-trade labels can improve standards and make supply chains more visible. Certification is not perfect and may exclude small producers or simplify complex labour conditions. Consumers should see labels as evidence, not proof of moral perfection. Strong labour law and producer bargaining power remain essential."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Workplace benefits", "Are workplace benefits more valuable than a higher salary?", "Benefits such as flexible hours, healthcare and training can improve security and quality of life. Their value depends on whether workers can actually use them and whether salaries remain fair. A higher salary offers freedom outside work, while benefits can reduce specific risks. Employees should compare the whole package rather than one headline figure."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Housing affordability", "What should governments do to make housing more affordable?", "Governments can build social housing, regulate unsafe rentals and encourage construction near transport. More supply alone will not help if homes become investment assets rather than places to live. Policies should protect tenants while supporting responsible development. Housing affordability is a public issue because it shapes education, work and family life."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Savings and experiences", "Is it wiser to save money or spend it on experiences?", "Saving creates security and protects people from unexpected costs, while experiences can strengthen relationships and provide lasting memories. The right balance depends on income and responsibilities. Spending every spare amount is risky, but refusing all enjoyment is also unsustainable. Good financial decisions leave room for both future stability and present life."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Economic inequality", "Why is economic inequality harmful even when average incomes rise?", "Average growth can hide a widening gap in access to housing, education and influence. Severe inequality weakens trust and limits opportunity because people begin life with very different resources. Differences in income are not automatically unjust, but societies need fair institutions and routes for mobility. Prosperity should be judged by distribution as well as size."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Green taxes", "Are green taxes fair if people cannot easily change their behaviour?", "A green tax can discourage pollution and fund cleaner alternatives, but it is unfair when households have no practical transport or energy choice. Governments should return revenue through support and invest in alternatives before raising costs sharply. Environmental responsibility requires realistic options, not only higher prices."],
  ["Consumer & economy", "Consumer data", "Should consumers be paid when companies profit from their personal data?", "People create valuable data through everyday activity, so compensation may seem fair. Direct payment could also encourage companies to collect even more information and make privacy a product for those who need money. Strong limits on collection and meaningful consent are more important than small individual payments. Data rights should not depend on bargaining power."],

  ["Values & relationships", "Honesty at work", "Is complete honesty always the best policy in a professional workplace?", "Honesty builds trust, but bluntly sharing every personal opinion can damage cooperation without improving a decision. Professional honesty should mean accurate information, clear motives and respectful timing. People can choose tact without lying. The aim is not to say everything, but to avoid misleading others when the truth matters."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Learning from failure", "Should people talk more openly about failure?", "Open discussion of failure can reduce shame and help others learn from decisions that did not work. Public stories often become too polished, so honesty requires acknowledging luck and support as well as mistakes. Failure should not be celebrated automatically, but analysing it can turn disappointment into useful knowledge."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Ambition", "Is ambition more likely to motivate people or make them unhappy?", "Ambition gives people direction and encourages them to develop skills. It becomes harmful when success is defined only by status or comparison, because every achievement creates a new standard. Healthy ambition includes values beyond winning. People can pursue difficult goals while protecting relationships and accepting that progress is not linear."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Digital and real friendship", "Are online friendships less dependable than friendships built through shared physical experiences?", "Digital friendships can be deeply supportive and may connect people who would never meet locally. Shared physical routines create a different kind of knowledge, since friends witness one another's ordinary lives. Dependability depends on consistency and care, not medium. Online friendship is strongest when people treat it with the same responsibility as any relationship."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Routines and change", "Do routines help people manage change or prevent them from adapting?", "Routines provide stability when circumstances are uncertain and reduce the effort needed for ordinary decisions. They can become restrictive when people defend them after their purpose has disappeared. Flexible routines offer the best balance: keep habits that support values and revise those that merely repeat the past."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Generosity", "Should generosity be judged by intention or by its results?", "Good intentions matter because they show a desire to help, but results reveal whether help was appropriate. A generous action can create dependence or ignore what people actually need. The most responsible generosity listens first and accepts correction. Kindness is not only about giving; it is about paying attention to consequences."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Public disagreement", "Why should people learn to disagree respectfully?", "Disagreement is unavoidable in a diverse society, and respectful argument allows decisions to improve without turning opponents into enemies. Respect does not mean avoiding strong criticism; it means addressing ideas rather than inventing motives. People who can disagree remain capable of cooperation after a decision is made."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Privacy in relationships", "How much privacy should people keep in close relationships?", "Trust does not require partners or friends to share every thought, message or private moment. At the same time, secrecy about decisions that affect another person can damage the relationship. Healthy privacy protects individuality, while honest communication protects shared responsibility. Closeness should not become ownership."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Meaningful success", "What does a successful life mean beyond professional achievement?", "Professional achievement can provide purpose, financial security and the satisfaction of mastering a skill. It is only one part of a life, since health, relationships and contribution also shape fulfilment. Success should be defined deliberately rather than inherited from advertising or social comparison. A meaningful life is measured by what it makes possible for oneself and others."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Cultural identity", "Can people have more than one cultural identity?", "People often inherit several languages, traditions and histories, and these identities can change across different settings. Multiple belonging does not make a person less loyal; it creates a wider sense of connection. Societies should allow identities to overlap instead of demanding a single, pure definition of who someone is."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Empathy in leadership", "Is empathy essential for effective leadership?", "Empathy helps leaders understand how decisions affect people and notice problems before they become crises. It should not mean avoiding difficult standards or agreeing with everyone. Effective leaders combine empathy with clarity and accountability. Understanding another person's position makes firm decisions more humane and often more realistic."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Saying no", "Why do many people find it difficult to say no?", "People may fear disappointing others, losing opportunities or appearing unhelpful. Constant agreement creates hidden resentment and makes commitments less reliable. Saying no respectfully protects time and clarifies priorities. A useful refusal can include an alternative, but it should not require a long apology for having limits."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Competition", "Does competition bring out the best in people?", "Competition can provide a clear goal and motivate people to improve. It can also make cooperation seem like weakness and encourage people to value winning over learning. Healthy competition has fair rules and recognises effort as well as results. People perform best when challenge exists without destroying mutual respect."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Apologies", "What makes an apology meaningful?", "A meaningful apology names the harm, accepts responsibility and changes behaviour. Saying sorry without acknowledging consequences can sound like a request to end an uncomfortable conversation. The injured person may not be ready to forgive immediately. Apology begins repair, but trust is rebuilt through consistent action."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Time alone", "Is spending time alone necessary for a balanced life?", "Time alone allows people to process experiences and make choices without constant social pressure. Too much isolation can deepen anxiety, so solitude should not be confused with disconnection. A balanced life includes both private reflection and shared activity. The right amount depends on personality, circumstances and the quality of relationships."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Trust in institutions", "How can public institutions regain trust when people become suspicious of them?", "Institutions regain trust through visible competence, clear explanations and accountability when mistakes occur. Public relations cannot replace evidence that services work fairly. Citizens also need access to information and meaningful ways to challenge decisions. Trust is not demanded by authority; it is earned through repeated behaviour."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Personal responsibility", "How far should individuals be held responsible for problems shaped by society?", "Individuals make choices, but those choices are influenced by income, education, design and public policy. Responsibility should therefore be shared rather than used to blame people for conditions they cannot control. Personal action still matters, especially when people have real alternatives. Fair judgement distinguishes between choice and constraint."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Generational learning", "What can younger and older generations learn from one another?", "Older people may offer experience, historical memory and patience, while younger people often bring new technology and different assumptions. Neither perspective is automatically wiser. Learning happens when generations work together rather than speak about one another. Respect should allow advice to be questioned and new ideas to be tested."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Resilience", "Is resilience mainly a personal quality or a social responsibility?", "Personal resilience helps people recover from setbacks, but no one should be expected to endure unsafe conditions indefinitely. Supportive relationships, fair institutions and access to rest make recovery more possible. Resilience is strongest when individuals develop coping skills and society reduces avoidable harm. Strength should not become an excuse for neglect."],
  ["Values & relationships", "Advice to the future self", "What advice would you give your future self about making important decisions?", "I would advise my future self to separate urgency from importance and to ask who will be affected by a decision. Short-term approval can be tempting, but values become visible through repeated choices. I would also leave room to change my mind when new evidence appears. A good decision is not one that avoids uncertainty, but one made honestly within it."],
];

window.writingPrompts = writingsBank.map(([category, title, prompt, example], index) => {
  const level = index % 20 < 10 ? 'C1' : 'B2';
  return {
    id: index + 1,
    category,
    title,
    level,
    difficulty: level === 'C1' ? 'High' : 'Medium',
    wordRange: level === 'C1' ? '260–320 words' : '180–250 words',
    prompt,
    example
  };
});
